[1]
Date: Sun, 17 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promed.mail.org>
Source: ProLog / AFP 16 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://www.ptd.net/webnews/wed/co/Qswiss-madcow.RQDL_CNG.html>

Switzerland discovers 2 new cases of mad cow disease
---------------------------------------------------
In Switzerland, 2 new cases of mad cow disease have been discovered in the
western and central cantons of Fribourg and Lucerne, the national
veterinary office said on Sat, 16 Nov 2002.
The discoveries bring to 21 the total number of cases of Bovine Spongiform
Encephalopathy (BSE) identified in Switzerland since the start of the year.
A total of 42 cases of the deadly brain-wasting disease were recorded in
Switzerland in 2001, against 33 the previous year.
Switzerland relaxed in July 2002 its BSE slaughter rules, announcing that
it would stop automatically slaughtering all descendants of cattle which
are found to have the disease from the start of next year.
The decision was made on the basis of evidence showing that mother-to-calf
transmission was extremely rare and that a risk existed only in the 2 years
preceding diagnosis of the disease.
******
[2]
Date: 9 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency via COMTEX, 8 Nov 2002 [edited]

Italy has 80 confirmed "mad cow" disease cases
---------------------------------------------
The number of confirmed cases in Italy of "mad cow" disease, or bovine
spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), has risen to 80 following tests on tissue
samples from 2 cows, the Health Ministry announced Friday.
The tests were carried out at a special laboratory in Turin. One of the
cows was from the province of Mantua and the other from Treviso.
Italy has so far carried out over 1 million tests for the brain-wasting
disease since it launched a BSE testing program in Jan 2001 in compliance
with the European Union regulations. All cows over 24 months old now have
to undergo such testing prior to slaughter.
A government task force was set up and BSE control measures were introduced
last February after the discovery of the first suspected case of the human
form of the brain-wasting disease, variant Creutzfeldt-Jacob Disease
(vCJD), in a young Sicilian woman. The case of vCJD was confirmed last month.
[During 2001, 50 BSE cases were recorded in Italy. Since the publication of
this posting, 3 additional cases have been identified, bringing the total
number of BSE cases in Italy accumulating during the current year to 33. -
Mod.AS]
