[3]
Date: Wed, 20 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CompuServe Our World, 20 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://ourworld.cs.com/j1braakman/nov02/denmark10.htm>

Denmark confirms 10th case of mad cow disease
---------------------------------------------
Denmark's 10th case of mad cow disease was confirmed Wed, 20 Nov 2002,
veterinary authorities said.
The Danish Veterinary and Food Administration said that 2 tests were done
on a 4-year-old milking cow that was found dead in early November, adding
that both tests were positive.
The cow was part of a herd of 108 animals that was quarantined after being
tested on 6 Nov 2002. The carcass was destroyed, and all the animals on the
farm in the northern part of the Jutland peninsula in western Denmark will
be killed. Other 7 cows sold to 4 different Danish farms will be destroyed,
too.
Per Kuhlman-Schaap, an agency spokesman, said 74 cows had been exported
from the farm to the Netherlands, 4 to Poland, and 2 to Kuwait since 2000.
He said a decision on the fate of those animals is the responsibility of
those countries.
Denmark's most recent BSE case was reported 23 Oct 2002 in a milking cow at
a farm in Jutland. In this Scandinavian country, 10 cases of BSE -- 9 in
Danish-born cows and 1 in a cow imported from Scotland in 1992 -- have been
detected.
[The following complementary information is derived from another posting on
the same issue in the same web-site and of the same date (kindly translated
from Danish by Dr Hanna Adler - thanks!]
"The cow died on the farm and was sent for incineration. From there,
according to the prevailing routine, a sample was sent for BSE testing to a
private laboratory. On 6 Nov 2002 the sample tested positive. A brain
sample was then sent to Denmark`s Veterinary Institute ,which confirmed the
diagnosis on 20 Nov 2002.
As a result, the following steps have been undertaken:
1.The whole herd from which the cow originated and all animals sold to
other farms will be killed and incinerated. Animals older then 24 months
from the herd will be tested for BSE.
2.The Danish Plant Directorate is looking for a potential feed-related
source of transmission. The result will be published later.
3.The case will be made known to other countries through Danish embassies
and delegations.
The current BSE situation in Denmark is as follows:
Counting this last case of Mad Cow Disease, there have been 10 cases of BSE
in Danish-born cattle: one case during 2000, 6 during 2001 and 3 during
2002. In addition, there was one case in an imported animal from Scotland
in 1992 and one in an animal exported from Denmark to Portugal.
The incidence of the disease in Denmark must still be considered low and
the number of cases for 2002 is not expected to deviate from the latest
prognosis". - Mod.AS]
