[5]
Date: Fri, 22 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ireland-on-line, 22 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://breakingnews.iol.ie/news/story.asp?j=54948686&p=5494939z>

New BSE cases uncovered this week
---------------------------------------
The Department of Agriculture has uncovered 5 new cases of BSE this week,
bringing the total number of cases so far this year to 303.
The new cases were detected in Meath, Cavan, Cork, Laois, and Louth, all
but one of them through an increased active surveillance programme
initiated in July 2001.
More than 587 000 cattle destined for human consumption have been tested
under this scheme so far this year.
******
[6]
Date: Fri, 22 Nov 2002
Sender: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Irish Independent, 22 Nov 2002, via CompuServe Our World [edited]
<http://ourworld.cs.com/j1braakman/nov02/farmer.htm>

Farmer jailed for BSE cattle scam
---------------------------------
A farmer who bought 150 calves illegally imported from the North contrary
to BSE controls was yesterday sentenced to 4 months' jail and fined 10 000
Irish Pounds for his part in the scam. [This person], from Bellisle,
Clonlara, Co Clare, bought the calves for around 63 I.P. from a rogue
importer between October 2000 and January 2001 when they were worth double
that here, Limerick District Court was told.
In sentencing the defendant, Judge Tom O'Donnell said the accused man was
motivated by greed "pure and simple". The [36 year old]
father-of-2 pleaded guilty to 22 sample counts yesterday out of a total of
111, with the remaining 89 taken into account.
He was also charged with failing to keep a register as required by
regulations, being in possession of animals bearing confusing ear tags, and
recklessly including on an application form tag particulars which he knew
to be false.
Veterinary inspector Mary Burke told the court that in April last year at
the height of the foot and mouth scare, she received confidential
information from a reliable informant that [this individual] had up to 150
imported calves on his farm. The information was given to her after the
outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease and people were worried over the
possibility that there might be other infected animals imported into the
jurisdiction.
From 1996 it became illegal to import animals from the North because of
the outbreak of BSE. "If a calf was imported and given a false identity,
our traceability system would be worthless," she added. "This is by far the
biggest in the state that we are aware of."
[Byline: Eugene Hogan]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Ireland was the first non-UK country to discover BSE in native cattle,
with its first cases recorded already in 1989. Since then, 1146 cases have
been reported. The recently observed increase -- from 246 cases in 2001 to
303 cases during 10.5 months in 2002 -- is cause for concern, certainly for
an exporting country and compared to the decrease observed in most other EU
countries (excluding Spain and the Netherlands). It might indicate
underreporting and probably significant illegal animal movements in
previous years, as demonstrated in the above report. - Mod.AS]
